{
  "texts": [
    "Diffusion-based neural networks iteratively refine the input by gradually reducing noise over several steps, starting from a random noise distribution and eventually converging to a desirable, coherent output distribution.",
    "In medical imaging, diffusion models have been applied to synthesize detailed organ structures and remove noise from imaging scans, enhancing clarity and diagnostic utility.",
    "For instance, Kazerouni et al. (2022) explored the efficacy of diffusion models for synthesizing three-dimensional medical imagery, covering a spectrum of anatomical areas, including the cerebrum, thorax, mammary glands, and knees, utilizing both MRI and CT scans.",
    "These models underwent training using datasets accessible to the public, subsequently creating synthetic images that radiologists with expertise deemed high in quality and anatomically accurate, thereby emphasizing the potential of diffusion models in enhancing medical image synthesis.",
    "In paleontology, these models have the potential to be adapted to reconstruct high-quality images of fossils from noisy or incomplete data, aiding in tasks like identifying subtle morphological features or segmenting fossil fragments from surrounding matrix, especially when dealing with low-quality or fragmented fossil records."
  ]
}